## 5. Authentication Strategy — The Most Important Decision

**The problem:** After login, your backend returns a JWT token. Where do you store it in the browser?

### Option A: localStorage
```
Pros:  Simple. Survives page refresh. Easy to read.
Cons:  Vulnerable to XSS (Cross-Site Scripting).
       Any JavaScript on the page can read it.
       If your app has a script injection bug, attacker steals token.
```

### Option B: httpOnly Cookie
```
Pros:  JavaScript CANNOT read it (browser enforces this).
       Immune to XSS attacks.
       Automatically sent with every request.
Cons:  Requires backend to set the cookie (CORS config changes needed).
       More complex to implement.
       Vulnerable to CSRF (different attack, different defense).
```

### Option C: In-Memory (React state / Zustand)
```
Pros:  Cannot be stolen by XSS. Never touches storage.
Cons:  Disappears on page refresh. User must log in again.
       Bad UX for most apps.
```

> **Open Question #3:** For this project, which storage approach do you think balances security and developer simplicity? There is no universally "correct" answer — it depends on your threat model.
>
> Hint: Most production apps use httpOnly cookies. Most tutorial apps use localStorage. We should discuss which to use here and why.

