## 6. Authorization Strategy — Protecting Routes

**The problem:** A customer should not be able to access `/admin`. How do we enforce this?

### Approach: Middleware-based Route Guards

Next.js has a `middleware.ts` file that runs before every request — on the server, before the page loads. We can:

1. Read the token from cookies
2. Decode it to get the role
3. Redirect if unauthorized

```
User goes to /admin
     ↓
middleware.ts runs first (server-side)
     ↓
No token? → redirect to /login
Token exists but role = "customer"? → redirect to /
Role = "admin"? → allow through
```

> **Open Question #4:** Why is it important to do this check on the server (middleware) rather than just hiding the link in the UI?

